"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145238","Home Office","false","2019-10-07","<p>The UK ended the routine detention of families with children in immigration removal centres in 2010, and enshrined this in law under the Immigration Act 2014. Children may be detained in family groups for removal in our pre-departure accommodation for up to 72 hours, extendable to a week with Ministerial approval. This provision is used sparingly and only after all other avenues have failed. Families with children may also be detained at the border pending a decision on whether they should be admitted to the country, or until the next available return flight if they are refused entry to the UK. There remain limited circumstances where unaccompanied children may be held under immigration powers at port for up to 24 hours, usually until they can be transferred into the care of social services.</p><p>Information on the number of children leaving detention and in the detention estate, is available in tables dt_09_q and dt_13_q of the detention tables in the latest release of ‘Immigration Statistics, year ending June 2019’. <br>The term 'deportations' refers to a legally-defined subset of returns which are enforced either following a criminal conviction or when it is judged that a person’s removal from the UK is conducive to the public good. Information on those deported is not separately available and therefore the published detention statistics refer to all enforced returns and voluntary departures.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL17763 ; HL17764","2019-10-07T17:09:49.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145238/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145238/answer","DetentionTables - June 2019.xlsx","Detention Tables - June 2019","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145238/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-05","Immigrants: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many children who have been detained in immigration detention at any point since January 2018 were subsequently deported.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL17765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145239","Department for International Trade","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">Licensing data is published as Official Statistics on GOV.UK. The data currently provides details of licences up to 31 March 2019 and this shows that 50 licence applications for military items have been approved. </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Information about the period 1 April to 30 June will be published on 15 October 2019 and data covering the period 1 July 2019 to 30 September 2019 will be published in January 2020.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Licensing decisions about transfers to Saudi Arabia of items which may be used in the conflict in Yemen have been subject to judicial review. Under the Court of Appeal judgment of 20 June 2019 my Rt. Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade was remitted to reconsider these decisions. Until such time the Government will not grant new licences to export items to Saudi Arabia or its coalition partners for possible use in Yemen. </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">All export licences are issued in strict accordance with the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.</ins></p><p> </p>",,"The Earl of Courtown",,"2019-09-09T16:39:49.153Z","2019-09-26T14:47:23.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145239/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145239/answer",,"The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145239/answer/previousversion/135494","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-09-05","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many export licences they have granted which approved the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia in 2019.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL17766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145240","Department for International Trade","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Court order of 20 June 2019 remitted the decision to grant export licences for the sale or transfer of arms and military equipment to Saudi Arabia for possible use in the conflict in Yemen to my Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade to re-take on the correct legal basis.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The order did not require the Secretary of State to suspend existing licences. As a matter of priority, and without prejudice to our appeal against the 20 June judgment, we are considering the implications of the judgment for decision-making.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Amending our decision-making process in line with the judgment does not necessarily mean that decisions would be different.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">On 20 June, the then Secretary of State, set out in a statement to Parliament that until we retake our licensing decisions in line with the judgment we will not grant any new licences for exports to Saudi Arabia and its coalition partners that might be used in the conflict in Yemen.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> </ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">However, you will be aware of the Secretary of State’s statement to Parliament of 26 September, in which she set out information on inadvertent breaches of the Undertaking given to the Court of Appeal by the then Secretary of State in the Order of the Court dated 20 June 2019 and licences that were granted contrary to the wider commitment to Parliament, made in a statement that same day. The Secretary of State has apologised unreservedly for these errors, both to the Court and Parliament.</ins></p>",,"The Earl of Courtown",,"2019-09-09T16:42:25.067Z","2019-10-02T14:22:11.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145240/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145240/answer",,"The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145240/answer/previousversion/135518","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-09-05","Arms Trade: Saudi Arabia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to (1) revoke all existing, and (2) ban future, export licences for the sale of arms to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL17767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145241","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>A portrait of Her Majesty The Queen is on display in the public area of Stormont House, alongside a series of images celebrating the work of the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Office does not have a specific policy on the display of pictures, and there is no general policy either requiring the display of pictures of Her Majesty The Queen, or removing them from display. In practice, the display of pictures changes from time to time, in response to factors such as redecoration, Ministerial wishes, and to reflect our work for example.</p><p> </p><p>The Department takes its responsibilities under Fair Employment legislation seriously and operates in line with the Equality Commission of Northern Ireland’s Guide, <em>Promoting a Good and Harmonious Working Environment</em>. This is the same for all of our offices.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank","HL17769","2019-10-01T15:03:12.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145241/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145241/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-09-05","Northern Ireland Office: Art Works","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government who made the decision to put a portrait of Her Majesty the Queen back on display at Stormont House; who was consulted before that decision was taken; on what date that decision was taken; and whether any additional images reflecting the work of the Northern Ireland Office were also put on display at the same location at that time.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL17768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145242","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>A portrait of Her Majesty The Queen is on display in the public area of Stormont House, alongside a series of images celebrating the work of the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Office does not have a specific policy on the display of pictures, and there is no general policy either requiring the display of pictures of Her Majesty The Queen, or removing them from display. In practice, the display of pictures changes from time to time, in response to factors such as redecoration, Ministerial wishes, and to reflect our work for example.</p><p> </p><p>The Department takes its responsibilities under Fair Employment legislation seriously and operates in line with the Equality Commission of Northern Ireland’s Guide, <em>Promoting a Good and Harmonious Working Environment</em>. This is the same for all of our offices.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank","HL17768","2019-10-01T15:03:12.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145242/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145242/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-09-05","Northern Ireland Office: Art Works","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what criteria are used to decide which images reflecting the work of the Northern Ireland Office are put on display at Stormont House; and whether different criteria are used to decide which images are displayed at 1 Horse Guards Road, London.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL17769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145243","Department of Health and Social Care","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p><ins class="ministerial">The Department has no plans to introduce a snack tax.</ins></p></ins></p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-09-09T16:57:36.097Z","2019-09-30T11:21:12.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145243/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145243/answer",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145243/answer/previousversion/135702","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-05","Food: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to introduce a snack tax to help reduce obesity.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145244","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</del><ins class="ministerial">The Spending Round settlement for local government responds to the pressures councils are facing by providing access to the largest increase in Core Spending Power since 2015. This includes an additional £1 billion of grant funding for adults and children’s social care, on top of the continuation of existing social care grants. Decisions about the distribution of funding for local government in 2020-21 will be announced in due course.</ins></p><p> </p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2019-09-09T16:38:38.077Z","2019-10-02T11:02:04.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145244/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145244/answer",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145244/answer/previousversion/135457","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-09-05","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to change the distribution of adult social care funding.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145245","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Government has committed to an extra 1,500 undergraduate medical school places - a 25% increase taking the total number of medical school training places in England to 7,500. The first 630 places were taken up in September 2018 with a further 690 places available in September 2019. The remaining additional 180 places will have been made available by universities by 2020/21. By 2020, five new medical schools will have opened in England to help deliver the expansion.</p><p>Following graduation from medical school, eligible applicants are allocated a place on the United Kingdom Foundation Programme.</p><p>The number of medical specialty training places that are available each year is set by Health Education England and based on their assessment of service gaps and predicted workforce needs.</p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan set out the need to ensure a sustainable overall balance between supply and demand across all staff groups. For doctors, it also focussed on reducing geographical and specialty imbalances. Subsequently, the interim NHS People Plan set out the action we will take now and over the long term to meet the challenges of supply, reform, culture and leadership, and changes in demand for health care. Actions include reviewing what further expansion in undergraduate medical places will be needed, in light of future plans made locally by sustainability and transformation partnerships and integrated care systems; and the establishment of a national programme board to address geographic and specialty shortages in doctors.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-09-09T16:55:33.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145245/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145245/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-05","Doctors: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps the NHS is taking to increase the number of trainee doctors recruited each year.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145246","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. I will correspond directly with the noble Lord.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Department requires that all applications to leave part or all of an installation or pipeline in place at the time of decommissioning are supported by a detailed environmental impact assessment. The assessment must comply with international obligations, is reviewed by Departmental staff and relevant stakeholders, including environmental bodies and NGOs, and must be accepted by the Department before it approves the proposed operations. Details of projects under consideration can be found on our web page titled “Oil and gas: decommissioning of offshore installations and pipelines” on the gov.uk website.</ins></p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-09-09T16:26:48.937Z","2019-10-02T14:19:37.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145246/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145246/answer",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145246/answer/previousversion/135198","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-05","North Sea: Oil Rigs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the environmental impact of leaving de-commissioned oil rigs in the North Sea.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL17773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145247","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2019-09-26","<p>The Government currently has no plans to proceed with the Non-Domestic Rating (Public Lavatories) Bill (HL), nor any plans to lay a carry-over motion before the end of the current session.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2019-09-26T12:38:17.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145247/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145247/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2019-09-05","Non-domestic Rating (Public Lavatories) Bill (HL)","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House when they intend to proceed with the Non-Domestic Rating (Public Lavatories) Bill [HL]; and whether they will lay a carry-over motion for that bill before the end of the current session.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL17774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145248","Women and Equalities","false","2019-09-27","<p>The Government is currently considering the Women and Equalities Select Committee’s report on ‘Enforcing the Equality Act: the law and the role of the EHRC’, which includes recommendations relating to the Public Sector Equality Duty. We will be responding to this report in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-09-27T13:23:34.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145248/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145248/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2019-09-05","Public Sector: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to review the workings of the Public Sector Equality Duty.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL17775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145249","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>HMS BRISTOL left active service in 1991 but remains a commissioned ship in the Royal Navy. She currently provides an alongside training and accommodation facility at the shore training establishment HMS EXCELLENT. Having been converted to provide this facility, she could not be returned to active service.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2019-09-09T16:25:55.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145249/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145249/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-05","HMS Bristol","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Goldie on 2 August (HL17439), who now owns HMS Bristol.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL17776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145250","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>There are currently six Type 45 Destroyers and 13 Type 23 Frigates in service with the Royal Navy.</p><p>There are no destroyers on order. Three Type 26 Frigates are currently on order. We plan to award a contract for five Type 31 Frigates by the end of 2019, and a contract for the second batch of five Type 26 Frigates in the early 2020s.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie","HL17778","2019-09-09T16:34:34.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145250/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145250/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-05","Warships: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many (1) destroyers, and (2) frigates, are presently on order for the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL17777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145251","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>There are currently six Type 45 Destroyers and 13 Type 23 Frigates in service with the Royal Navy.</p><p>There are no destroyers on order. Three Type 26 Frigates are currently on order. We plan to award a contract for five Type 31 Frigates by the end of 2019, and a contract for the second batch of five Type 26 Frigates in the early 2020s.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie","HL17777","2019-09-09T16:34:34.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145251/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1145251/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-05","Warships","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many (1) destroyers, and (2) frigates, are presently in service with the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL17778"
