"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144615","Cabinet Office","false","2019-09-09","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold this information. The issuing of fixed penalty notices is at the discretion of individual Electoral Registration Officers, who hold this data. It should be noted that penalties exist for failing to respond to requests for information from EROs (such as not completing a Household Enquiry Form or an Invitation to Register) rather than for failing to register to vote.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-09-09T15:02:21.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144615/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144615/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-04","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of people have received fixed penalty notices for failing to register on the electoral register in each local authority area since July 2014.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","286651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144616","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","true","2019-09-09","<p><del class="ministerial">None.</del> <ins class="ministerial"><em>The Commission has spent no money on this. </em></ins>Direct advertising (or marketing) does not form part of the Commission’s approach to its work encouraging voter registration.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2019-09-09T08:21:11.717Z","2019-09-09T13:41:11.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144616/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144616/answer","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144616/answer/previousversion/133677","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2019-09-04","Electoral Register: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, how much the Commission has spent on direct advertising in the last three years to increase registration of (a) young people aged 18 to 25 and (b) members of the expatriate community.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","286652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144617","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2019-09-09","<p>National Voter Registration Day was an initiative led by Bite the Ballot, which last took place in February 2016. As part of its activity to support the project, the Commission did not place any Facebook advertising.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2019-09-09T08:22:26.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144617/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144617/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2019-09-04","Electoral Register: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, how much the Electoral Commission spent on Facebook targeted advertisements for the purpose of increasing electoral registration on National Voter Registration Day in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","286653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144618","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>HSE does monitor year on year statistics of work-related stress, using data gathered via the Labour Force Survey.</p><p> </p><p>The overall incidence rates have remained fairly stable over the last decade but have recently shown indications of an upward trend. This data is used as evidence to inform policy and strategy development. Within the statistics there are a series of sectors that have persistently higher than average rates of stress – education, health, local and central government.</p><p> </p><p>HSE has targeted these sectors more specifically, and its involvement has led to the development of practical tools and guidance to help support employers and employees in taking action to prevent and reduce the incidence of work-related stress and resulting mental health issues of anxiety and depression.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-09-09T14:22:12.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144618/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144618/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-04","Employment: Stress","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Health and Safety Executive has made of the effect of long-term trends in workplace stress on the mental and physical health of workers.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","286654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144619","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-09-09","<p>Benefit sanctions are only used when people fail to meet their agreed work-related conditionality requirements without good reason.</p><p />","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-09-09T14:11:05.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144619/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144619/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether benefit sanctions are applied in cases where parole or probation conditions have not been met satisfactorily.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","286757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144620","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-09-09","<p>In order to safeguard operational effectiveness, the Armed Forces are exempt from the provisions of the 1998 National Minimum Wage (NMW) Act. Nevertheless, we aim to ensure that the Armed Forces are remunerated in line with NMW provisions.</p><p>The daily pay offered to Part-Time Volunteer Reserve (PTVR) personnel is derived from the equivalent annual salary paid to their Regular counterparts. The annual salary is made up of base pay plus X-Factor, the latter reflecting the different conditions in Service life experienced by members of the Armed Forces compared to conditions in civilian life, averaged over a whole career and across all three Services. All pay rates, including X-Factor percentages, are recommended by the independent Armed Forces' Pay Review Body (AFPRB). At present, full-time Regular personnel are paid X-Factor at 14½% and PTVR personnel get 5% X-Factor. In giving their recommendations, the AFPRB give due consideration to the needs of the Services to recruit and retain suitably able, motivated and qualified people.</p><p>Following the Government's acceptance of the AFPRB's most recent recommendations (HCWS1770), the current annual starting salary for a Regular private or equivalent (pay increment OR2-1) has risen to £20,000 p.a., whilst the equivalent PTVR annual salary, derived using the lower level of X-Factor, has risen to £18,341 p.a. PTVR daily rates of pay are calculated by dividing the annual salary by 365¼, and a day's pay is earned through voluntary attendance of eight hours or more. For an eight-hour day, this is the equivalent of £6.28 per hour. In addition, PTVR personnel are provided with additional payments in lieu of untaken leave, equivalent to just over 10% of their pay; they may also claim an annual tax-free training bounty of up £470 in their first year of service where they meet their unit's minimum training requirements (approximately 30 days' relevant attendance). When PTVR personnel are called-up, for example for operational deployment, they are paid the same annual salary as their Regular counterparts, i.e. the rate inclusive of the higher level of X-Factor, and they also gain access to the same range of allowances payable for Regular service.</p><p>This Government will continue to work with the independent AFPRB to ensure that all members of the Armed Forces are fairly remunerated for the work that they do.</p>","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","286772 ; 286773 ; 286774","2019-09-09T15:42:47.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144620/answer","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1144620/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-04","Reserve Forces: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how the daily rate of pay for armed forces reservists is calculated from the regular equivalents.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","286771"
